50|$|The {{pitot tube}} and static port on an {{aircraft}} {{are used to}} determine the airspeed of the aircraft. These two devices are connected to the <b>airspeed</b> <b>indicator,</b> which determines the dynamic pressure of the airflow past the aircraft. Dynamic pressure is the difference between stagnation pressure and static pressure. Bernoulli's principle is used to calibrate the <b>airspeed</b> <b>indicator</b> so that it displays the indicated airspeed appropriate to the dynamic pressure.|$|R
5000|$|Raoul Badin (class of 1910), one of {{the main}} inventors of the <b>airspeed</b> <b>indicator</b> and forefather of {{instrument}} flying.|$|R
