5000|$|... for {{aircraft}} control, CAS (and EAS) {{are the primary}} reference points, since they describe the dynamic pressure acting on aircraft surfaces regardless of density, altitude, wind, and other conditions. EAS {{is used as a}} reference by aircraft designers, but EAS cannot be displayed correctly at varying altitudes by a simple (single capsule) <b>airspeed</b> <b>indicator.</b> CAS is therefore a standard for calibrating the <b>airspeed</b> <b>indicator</b> such that CAS equals EAS at sea level pressure and approximates EAS at higher altitudes.|$|R
